07706nam a22012015i 9783110215366DE-B159720211217065530.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211217t20092009gw     fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)719449729  a97831102153667 a10.1515/97831102153662doi  a(DE-B1597)36046  a(OCoLC)558740440  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aP301.5.M48bM85 2009eb 7aLAN0090002bisacsh04a302.2222  aET 4252rvk0(DE-625)rvk/27982:00aMultimodal Metaphor /ced. by Charles J. Forceville, Eduardo Urios-Aparisi. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter Mouton, c[2009] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (470 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aApplications of Cognitive Linguistics [ACL] ,x1861-4078 ;v110 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  a"Metaphor studies" has over the past 30 years become a discipline in its own right, mainly because of the cognitive linguistic claim that metaphors characterize thought, not just language. But most metaphor scholars hitherto focus exclusively on its purely verbal expressions. Since both persuasive and narrative discourses in contemporary society increasingly draw on modalities other than language alone, sustained research into a broader range of manifestations of metaphor is imperative. This volume is the first book-length study to investigate multimodal occurrences of metaphor, and is of interest to scholars interested in metaphor as well as in multimodal discourse. Each chapter investigates metaphors whose identification and interpretation depend on the co-presence of at least two of the following modalities: language, visuals, gestures, sound, music. On the basis of case studies in a variety of discourse genres (advertising, cartoons, films, comics, conversation, music, amply represented in photographs, logos, drawings, film stills, and musical scores), the contributors demonstrate that, and how, metaphor can occur multimodally, providing ideas and methodological angles enabling further theorizing and testing in this rapidly expanding field. Covering creative as well as conceptual metaphors, and where appropriate evaluating cultural factors governing metaphor interpretation, the contributors provide a wealth of material for studying the conceptual and rhetorical force of metaphor in contemporary society.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 17. Dez 2021) 0aMetaphor. 4aKognitive Linguistik. 4aPragmatik. 4aVisuelle Kommunikation. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aCognitive linguistics.  apragmatics.  avisual communication.1 aCaballero, Rosario, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCienki, Alan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEerden, Bart, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEggertsson, Gunnar Theodór, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aForceville, Charles J., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aForceville, Charles, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKoller, Veronika, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMaes, Alfons, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMatsunaka, Yoshihiro, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMittelberg, Irene, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMüller, Cornelia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRefaie, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRohdin, Mats, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchilperoord, Joost, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb